english:
  title: A Lament for Master Pan Nam, with Preface
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alas, Master! When the Master lived, people doubted him. When the Master passed, their doubt only deepened.

    The worldly clever have silver tongues, their cunning smooth as panpipes. The fashionable follow without discernment, their compliance supple as reeds. But not the Master. He was silent, measured in speech. The Master upheld the righteous path and would not drift with the times. The small-minded suspected him of dullness, of slowness.

    The shrewd flock to power, the whole world chases fortune and rank. But not the Master. Rather than beg for scraps, he would starve in a ravine. Rather than seek false advancement, he would remain lowborn all his days. If this is goodness, he cherished it like precious orchids, even in the humblest beggar. If that is evil, he despised it like an enemy, even in the halls of the mighty. The small-minded suspected him of being impractical, of chasing phantoms.

    When death came, all men fear it, cling to life, endure shame and indignity, cry out in anguish. But not the Master. "Though my righteousness lead me into the jaws of beasts, I will not betray it for life. My body may be slain, but my Way cannot be bent." The small-minded suspected him of folly.

    Yet gentlemen said: The Master possessed the Way—it could honor the sovereign and shelter the people, yet the world would not receive it. The Master possessed learning—it could pierce the veil of ages, yet people would not believe it. His righteous countenance was stern, yet the petty grew angry. His loyal words were direct, yet those above would not hear. Thus they suspected the Master's fate was harsh, the times were dark.

    They said: The Master practiced goodness—it could bring blessing and long life, yet he enjoyed no longevity. It could leave a legacy for descendants, yet he could not preserve himself. Thus they suspected the Master was unlucky.

    But I say all their suspicions are wrong—they do not know the Master at all. Whether the Way prevails or fails depends on the times. Death and life, fortune and misfortune—these do not rest in mortal hands. What could the Master do but practice righteousness? When the Master lived, I believed in him. When he died, I believed all the more.

    The Master did not grow rich with the greedy and base, did not live alongside the false and flattering. Thus his death preserved his integrity, and his lack of status became his honor. Why doubt further?

    Then why do I weep? I weep that the people lost the Master's grace. I weep that the Way has nowhere to rest. I weep that we have no model to follow. I do not weep for the dead—I weep for the living.

    My lamentation says:

    Ah, Master, it is finished, it is finished.
    In an age of misfortune, the world knew you not.
    Seeing the world's peril, you could not bear to stay silent.
    Your small frame thrown again and again,
    Standing against the rivers' mad torrent.
    Swept away with none to rescue you,
    Your life was lost.
    The world judged you and named you mad.
    Yet I have found my ground—my heart is at peace.

    The worthy follow their straight path,
    But the foolish cannot be awakened.
    We betray righteousness to steal at life,
    Fluttering anxiously, seeking support.
    Ah, shame burns on our faces,
    Sorrow gathers in our hearts.
    If the earth could birth you again,
    I would follow only you to the nine springs below.
  footnotes:
    - Pan Nam (潘南) refers to Pan Sang-duk, a historical figure known for his principled resistance and refusal to compromise with corrupt authority.
    - The reference to 'nine springs below' (九原) alludes to the classical underworld, expressing the speaker's profound reverence and desire to follow the Master even in death.
    - The imagery of being 'swept away by rivers' references the Master's resistance to political corruption, suggesting he was destroyed by forces he could not overcome despite his moral stance.
